===============================================================================
SECTION 1: BASIC CLASS STRUCTURE
===============================================================================
Version 1: Empty Class

class Student:
    ...

def main():
    student = get_student()
    print(f'{student.name} from {student.house}')

def get_student():
    student = Student()
    student.name = input("Name: ")
    student.house = input("House: ")
    return student

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()

Key Points:
- class Student: Creates a blueprint/template.
- ... : Placeholder (ellipsis) for empty class.
- student = Student(): Instantiates an object.
- Attributes added dynamically: student.name, student.house.

Why This Structure?
- Creates custom data type grouping related data.
- Alternative to using separate variables or dictionaries.
- Provides reusability.

Problems with This Approach:
- Data setup is scattered.
- No guarantee all students have same attributes.
- Can accidentally forget to set attributes.

===============================================================================
SECTION 2: CONSTRUCTORS (__init__ METHOD)
===============================================================================
Version 2: Adding Constructor

class Student:
    def __init__(self, name, house=None):
        self.name = name
        self.house = house

What is __init__?
- Special method (constructor) automatically called when creating object.
- 'self' parameter refers to the instance being created.
- Parameters define required/optional data for object creation (e.g., house=None).



Key Changes from Version 1:
- Encapsulation: Data setup happens in ONE place (init).
- Atomic creation: Student(name, house) ensures object is created with data.

Warning:
Adding random attributes like 'student.father = input()' outside the class
creates "hidden" properties and breaks class template consistency.

===============================================================================
SECTION 3: INSTANCE METHODS
===============================================================================
Version 3: Adding Behavior with Methods

class Student:
    def __init__(self, name, house, patronus=None):
        self.name = name
        self.house = house
        self.patronus = patronus

    def charm(self):
        match self.patronus:
            case "Stag": return "🤣"
            case "Otter": return "😒"
            case _: return "🤩"

What are Instance Methods?
- Functions defined inside a class.
- First parameter is always 'self'.
- Operate on specific object instances using internal data (self.patronus).

Why Add Methods?
- Logic Encapsulation: Object knows its own behavior.
- Clean Code: main() just asks, doesn't figure out "how".

===============================================================================
SECTION 4: PROPERTIES (GETTERS & SETTERS)
===============================================================================
Version 4: Adding Encapsulation with Properties

@property
def house(self):
    return self._house

@house.setter
def house(self, house):
    self._house = house

Why Use Getters/Setters? (The REAL Reasons)
1. Validation (The "Bouncer"):
   Check if house is valid before saving it to self._house.
2. Abstraction:
   Change internal storage (e.g., splitting Name into First/Last) without 
   changing how the user accesses .name.
3. Read-Only Attributes:
   Provide a @property but NO setter.



===============================================================================
SECTION 5: CLASS METHODS
===============================================================================
Version 5: Factory Method Pattern

@classmethod
def get(cls):
    name = input("Name: ")
    house = input("House: ")
    return cls(name, house)

What are Class Methods?
- Decorated with @classmethod.
- First parameter is 'cls' (the class), not 'self'.
- The "Chicken and Egg" Solution: Allows calling Student.get() BEFORE an 
  object exists. It acts as a "Front Desk" or "Factory" for creation.



===============================================================================
SECTION 6: STATIC METHODS
===============================================================================
@staticmethod
def is_valid_name(name):
    return len(name) > 1

Comparison:
- @classmethod: Gets 'cls'. Can create objects (return cls()).
- @staticmethod: Gets nothing. Used for utility functions related to the class.

===============================================================================
SECTION 7: INHERITANCE
===============================================================================
Version 6: Parent and Child Classes

class Wizard:
    def __init__(self, name):
        self.name = name

class Student(Wizard):
    def __init__(self, name, house):
        super().__init__(name) # Call parent constructor
        self.house = house



Why Inheritance? (DRY Principle)
- Don't Repeat Yourself: Write name validation in Wizard once; reuse it 
  in Student, Professor, etc.

===============================================================================
SECTION 8: OOP CORE CONCEPTS
===============================================================================
1. ENCAPSULATION: Bundling data/methods and restricting direct access (Getters).
2. ABSTRACTION: Hiding complexity (e.g., student.charm() hides match/case logic).
3. INHERITANCE: Creating new classes based on existing ones.
4. POLYMORPHISM: Same interface (e.g., a print function) working with 
   different object types (Wizard, Student, Professor).

Public vs Private (By Convention):
- self.name : Public
- self._name : "Private" (Please don't touch directly)

===============================================================================
SECTION 9: SPECIAL METHODS (DUNDER METHODS)
===============================================================================
__init__ : Constructor (Object creation)
__str__  : User-friendly string (Called by print(obj))
__repr__ : Developer-friendly string (Debugging)
__len__  : Returns length (Called by len(obj))

